<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910228-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>910228-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Sony Forms Unit   To Link Software,   Hardware Lines   ----   By Patrick M. Reilly   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>02/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   SNE</CO><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Sony Corp., in another move to link itselectronic hardware and software operations, said it createda unit called Sony Electronic Publishing.   The new unit, which will be based here, will create anddistribute software for use in personal computers, electronicvideo games and other electronic hardware that is indevelopment at Sony and other manufacturers of consumerelectronics.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We will spend a good deal of time on video games andcomputer products, but there is a lot more in interactivemedia to come,&quot; said Olaf Olafsson, a Sony vice president forspecial projects who was named as the president of SonyElectronic Publishing. &quot;There will be great demands for newprogramming as new products appear,&quot; said the 31-year-old Mr.Olafsson, who was trained as a physicist and has writtenthree novels.   Sony Electronic Publishing aims to cash in on the imagesand music produced by Sony's record and movie companies. Itwill become part of Sony Software Corp., formed in January tohelp coordinate the global entertainment giant. Sony Softwareincludes Sony's movie and record units, including ColumbiaPictures Entertainment Inc., which Sony acquired in 1989, andSony Music Entertainment, the new name given to CBS Records,which Sony acquired three years ago.   Mr. Olafsson said some early projects for the new unitcould include a program on a rock music group on CD-ROM, acomputer attachment that enables users to see moving picturesand hear music. For example, Sony Electronic Publishing couldcreate a story featuring a Sony recording artist, using filmclips from a concert and text to explain the group's music.   Sony wouldn't disclose any specific properties the unit isworking on. But the group will also create software for itsSony Data Discman, a portable compact disk player that canstore dictionaries, novels or travel guides. Introduced inJapan last year, Discman has become popular among commuters,students and professionals such as lawyers. Discman isexpected to be available in the U.S. in the near future.   Another software product Sony is expected to introducethis year would include software for PCs that would bundletogether entire encyclopedias, multilanguage dictionaries,magazines, music and multimedia video games.   Mr. Olafsson said Sony Electronic Publishing will soonannounce new computer software created by partnerships withmagazine and book publishers, as well as with makers of videogames.</TEXT></DOC>